Vim Modes:
Vim has different modes. The two primary modes are:

Normal Mode: Used for navigation and manipulation of text.
Insert Mode: Used for inserting or editing text.

When you open a file, Vim starts in Normal Mode.


Basic Navigation in Normal Mode:
h, j, k, l: Move the cursor left, down, up, and right, respectively.
gg: Move to the beginning of the file.
G: Move to the end of the file.
:x: Save changes and exit Vim.


Switching to Insert Mode:
Press i to enter Insert Mode. Now you can type and edit text.


Saving Changes and Exiting:
In Normal Mode, type :w to save changes.
To save and exit, type :wq.
To exit without saving, type :q!.


Editing Text in Insert Mode:
Press Esc to switch from Insert Mode to Normal Mode.
Press a to append text after the cursor.
Press A to append text at the end of the line.


Deleting Text in Normal Mode:
x: Delete the character under the cursor.
dd: Delete the entire line.
D: Delete from the cursor position to the end of the line.


Copying and Pasting:
yy: Copy (yank) the current line.
p: Paste the text after the cursor.


Search and Replace:
/search_term: Search for a term.
n: Move to the next occurrence of the search term.
:%s/old_text/new_text/g: Replace all occurrences of "old_text" with "new_text" in the entire file.


Help:
To get help, press Esc to enter Normal Mode, then type :help.
